(1, '豐富，理智和清醒的成年人', 'Babies are always the life of any party', '<p>寶寶總是任何一方的生活，與家人和朋友想要去把握和擁抱你的小傢伙，並通過孩子身邊所有的享受和慶祝。只要你的寶寶是健康的，快樂的，沒有理由不包括在周邊冬季假期的慶祝活動。但是有一個正確的方式，包括你的小一的聚會，大約有一千錯誤的方法。讓我們幾個闡明權的最重要的兩點。需要記住的事情......最關鍵的是要記住的是，對於一個嬰兒，聖誕節和除夕只是另一天，當他們想餵像往常一樣晚上，及時改變運動臟尿布的時候，舉行和震撼的需要，並睡累了的時候。常規是嬰兒重要的，打破日常的，只是因為你說這是一次一方不為一個偉大的開始新的一年。不幸的是，如果你的寶寶不喜歡大聲喧嘩，需要睡覺一定的長度和時間在一定的條件下，還是有一個簡單的排除被周圍的很多人很多騷動的任何其他問題（削弱免疫系統為例），然後它在今年開始之前，工黨可能會結束。抱歉。第二個音符錘回家之前，我們得到了一些積極點（請記住，這是一個值得慶祝的時刻！）是一位經驗豐富的育兒提供商需要存在，也完全清醒。除夕特別是指酒，常常很多。這是偉大的所有負責任的成年人享受著黨，但至少有一個與成人最好可以享受不低於慶祝香檳單一的玻璃等等。如果任何嬰兒出席黨父母不在調用指定的照顧者，然後又經驗豐富，理智和清醒的成年人必須明確指定為提前保姆。永遠不要認為別人會只是&ldquo;照顧它&rdquo;;不依賴於喜愛的阿姨或爺爺愛好或其他任何人，除非他們已經專門考慮您的小傢伙照顧任務！你需要擁有的一切照顧者可能會派對開始前需要擺出來，從牛奶或配方，尿布，衣服的變化，等等，你需要有詳細討論孩子的需要。如果你想享受你的派對，打算為所有寶寶有關的東西，可以提前毀掉的時間吧！還有 - 現在，我們已經處理了更多的不愉快的話題。讓我們來談談如何與寶寶派對！保持雙手清潔，許多嬰兒喜歡運動，音樂，笑聲和關注。如果你是其中之一，那麼他們可以深入到慶祝活動;只是讓抱著孩子之前，確保人們洗手。當你的寶寶正在在短時間內舉行很多人，你應該洗自己的小手的加一步了。使用質量擦拭或讓別人幫你輕輕刷洗那些爪子用溫和的肥皂和水，每半小時左右，因為每次寶寶的小手指去那個小口，他們可能攝入的細菌是被潛伏在開胃共享拼盤，馬桶，雪茄等。但只要你保持你的寶寶清潔，只要他或她是幸福的，在黨。創造一個安靜的房間。如果你的寶寶是喧囂和騷動更加敏感，然後安排一個更明智的派對氣氛。一個偉大的方式做，這是指定一個房間作為空間更內斂的慶祝。讓美好時光，整個房子，但解釋說，在這一方面，都是值得歡迎的，但不是在同一時間。在此更安靜，更平靜房間時，人們可以旋轉數在時刻而不是由所有的動作所包圍的嬰兒。大家誰想要享受少年能做到這一點，和初級不必受到的節日慶典的全部力量。你可以保持獨立的小吃，小一點的盤子在這個房間裡，提供非酒精飲料的托盤，玩你知道你的孩子喜歡音樂，等等。慶祝早了一點當時間臨近新年響，記住，你的新生兒真的一點也不在乎什麼日曆說。如果你的寶寶是一個時間表，你已經克服了新的父母所面臨的最大挑戰之一。不要搞砸了只是為了保持清醒，當午夜的鐘聲敲響！相反，考慮看，如果你的朋友和家人會服從簡單地&ldquo;搬&rdquo;新年較早。這並不像聽起來那麼瘋狂：假裝你是在一個不同的時區，並開始新的一年幾小時的早期（AKA上床在老時間，但比平常多一點派對後）。你甚至可以找到一個慶祝活動發生在午夜在世界的另一部分在電視上或網上和那些人一起慶祝。 （例如，悉尼領先香港3個小時，而斐濟和新西蘭5小時領先。）你會發現大多數人會喜歡這樣的想法，尤其是你的老客人可能會很高興有一個傍晚反正和年輕人們總是可以穿梭過另一方，並在當天晚上慶祝2除夕午夜！</p>\r ', '<p><strong>Babies are always the life of any party, with friends and family wanting to hold and cuddle your little one and pass the baby around for all to enjoy and celebrate. As long as your baby is healthy and happy, there&rsquo;s no reason not to include them in the festivities surrounding the winter holidays. But there is a right way to include your little one in a party, and about a thousand wrong ways. Let&rsquo;s get a few of the most important points spelled out right. Things to remember... The most crucial thing to remember is that for a baby, Christmas Day and New Year&rsquo;s Eve are just another day and night when they want to be fed as usual, be changed promptly when sporting a dirty diaper, be held and rocked as needed, and to sleep when tired. Routine is crucial for an infant and breaking their routine just because you say it&rsquo;s time to party doesn&rsquo;t make for a great start to the new year. Unfortunately, if your baby hates loud noises, needs to sleep a certain length of time and in certain conditions, or has any other issues that simply preclude being around lots of people and lots of commotion (a weakened immune system, for example), then the party might be over before it starts this year. Sorry. The second note to hammer home before we get to some of the positive points (remember, this is a time to celebrate!) is that an experienced childcare provider needs to be present and also totally sober. New Year&rsquo;s Eve especially means booze, and often lots of it. That&rsquo;s great for all the responsible adults enjoying the party, but at least one of those adults had better be enjoying no more than a single glass of celebratory champagne. If a parent of any baby present at a party is not the designated caregiver on call, then another experienced, sensible and sober adult must be specifically designated as the babysitter ahead of time. Don&rsquo;t ever assume someone will just &ldquo;take care of it&rdquo;; don&rsquo;t rely on that favorite aunt or loving grandfather or anyone else unless they have been specifically tasked with taking care of your little one! You need to have everything a caregiver might need laid out before a party starts, from milk or formula, diapers, clothing changes, etc. and you need to have discussed your child&rsquo;s needs in detail. If you want to enjoy your party, plan for all the baby-related things that could ruin it ahead of time! There - now we&rsquo;ve dealt with the more unpleasant topics. Let&rsquo;s talk about how to party with that baby! Keep hands clean Many babies enjoy motion, music, laughter and attention. If yours is one of those, then they can dive right into the celebrations; just make sure people wash their hands before holding your child. And when your baby is being held by lots of people in a short period of time, you should take the added step of washing their little hands, too. Use a quality wipe or have someone help you gently scrub those paws with mild soap and water every half hour or so, because every time your baby&rsquo;s little fingers go in that little mouth, they might be ingesting germs that were lurking on shared platters of appetizers, toilet seats, cigars, and so on. But as long as you&rsquo;re keeping your baby clean and as long as he or she is happy, party on. Create a quiet room If your baby is more sensitive to noise and commotion, then arrange for a more sensible party atmosphere. One great way to do this is to designate a room as a space for a more restrained celebration. Let the good times roll throughout the house, but explain that in this one area, all are welcome, but not at the same time. In this quieter, calmer room, people can rotate a few at a time rather than having the baby surrounded by all the action. Everyone who wants to enjoy Junior can do so, and Junior need not be subjected to the full force of a holiday bash. You can keep separate, smaller plates of snacks in this room, offer a tray of nonalcoholic beverages, play music you know your child likes, and so on. Celebrate a little early When the time draws near to ring in the New Year, remember that your newborn really couldn&rsquo;t care less about what the calendar says. If your baby is on a schedule, you have already overcome one of the greatest challenges new parents face. Don&rsquo;t screw it up just to be awake when the clock strikes midnight! Instead consider seeing if your friends and family would be amenable to simply &ldquo;moving&rdquo; the New Year earlier. This isn&rsquo;t as crazy as it sounds: just pretend you&rsquo;re in a different time zone and start the New Year a few hours early (AKA go to bed at the usual time, but after a bit more partying than usual). You can even find a celebration occurring at midnight in another part of the world on TV or online and celebrate along with those folks. (For example, Sydney is 3 hours ahead of Hong Kong, while Fiji and New Zealand are 5 hours ahead.) You&rsquo;ll find most people will love this idea, especially as your older guests will likely be glad to have an early evening anyway, and the younger folks can always shuttle off to another party and celebrate two New Year&rsquo;s Eve midnights in the same evening!</strong></p>\r ', 'MK.jpg,03(pp_w1200_h951).png,top01.jpg,top02.jpg,top03.jpg', '1', '2015-02-12 09:04:39', 0),
(14, 'DC漫畫推出克里超級英雄', 'DC Comics Introduces Cree Superhero', '<p>DC漫畫最近推出了一個新的超級英雄：一個16歲的克里女孩駝鹿廠，安大略省，誰的推移名稱春分。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>性格將是一個五問題系列具有正義聯盟加拿大，一隊超級英雄的總部設在安大略省北部的部分。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>春分是由傑夫&middot;雷賽，一本漫畫書藝術家和作家創造。勒邁爾生長在一個小的農業小鎮在安大略省，現居多倫多。他寫的故事為其他DC漫畫人物，其中包括綠箭和超人。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>當雷賽是提供給寫的美國人物正義聯盟的機會 - 頂級DC超級英雄 - 他建議這個故事在加拿大進行設置。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>他選擇了北安大略的位置，因為他認為鄉村環境將讓故事更加明顯加拿大人。他也認為這將是有趣的，看看超級英雄比大城市以外的地方。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>勒邁爾曾訪問過北安大略，當他還是個孩子，他感興趣的是第一民族的文化和故事，他了解那裡。他決定創建一個超級英雄誰是克里和女性，因為他想提出一個觀點，個性與其他超級英雄，誰是多為白色和男性不同。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>研究他的故事，雷賽了好幾趟麋工廠和穆索尼，在安大略省北部兩個小鎮。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>城鎮位於穆斯河附近的詹姆斯灣，哈德遜灣南端。有沒有道路通往社區。他們只能通過火車或飛機到達。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>勒邁爾花時間談論到當地人民 - 尤其是學生 - 讓想法和反饋他們。他甚至組織了一場競賽中，學生可以建議超能力的新角色。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>春分，本名Miiyahbin，擁有的權力，來自於地球和隨季節變化。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>勒邁爾說，春分是由Shannen Koostachin，從Attawapiskat第一個國家十幾歲，這也是近詹姆斯灣靈感的一部分。 Shannen帶動一個系列有建於她的社區適當的學校。她在一次車禍中去世，2010年，在15歲的時候，而是一個新的學校，她的名字命名，坐落在9月開業。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>藝術的春分故事是由Mike McKone，誰也說明了許多漫畫的DC和Marvel公司。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>相關網站<br />\r\n克里印度概況</p>\r\n\r\n<p>克里人物和傳說</p>\r\n\r\n<p>有關Shannen Koostachin和她的競選的更多信息</p>\r\n', '<p>DC Comics recently introduced a new superhero: a 16-year-old Cree girl from Moose Factory, Ontario, who goes by the name&nbsp;<em>Equinox</em>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The character will be part of a five-issue series featuring Justice League Canada, a team of superheroes based in Northern Ontario.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Equinox was created by Jeff Lemire, a comic book artist and writer. Lemire grew up in a small farming town in Ontario and now lives in Toronto. He has written stories for other DC Comics characters, including Green Arrow and Superboy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When Lemire was offered the chance to write for the Justice League of America characters &ndash; the top DC superheroes &ndash; he suggested the story be set in Canada.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He chose Northern Ontario for the location because he thought a rural setting would make the story more distinctly Canadian. He also thought it would be interesting to see superheroes somewhere other than big cities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lemire had visited Northern Ontario when he was a child, and he was interested in the First Nations culture and stories he learned about there. He decided to create a superhero who is Cree and female because he wanted to present a perspective and personality that are different from other superheroes, who are mostly white and male.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To research his stories, Lemire made several trips to Moose Factory and Moosonee, two small towns in Northern Ontario.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The towns are located on the Moose River near James Bay, at the southern tip of Hudson Bay. There are no roads leading to the communities. They can be reached only by train or plane.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lemire spent time talking to local people &ndash; especially students &ndash; to get ideas and feedback from them. He even organized a contest in which students could suggest super powers for the new character.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Equinox, whose real name is Miiyahbin, has powers that come from the Earth and change with the seasons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lemire says Equinox was inspired in part by Shannen Koostachin, a teenager from Attawapiskat First Nation which is also near James Bay. Shannen led a campaign to have a proper school built in her community. She died in a car accident in 2010 at the age of 15, but a new school, named after her, is set to open in September.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The art for the Equinox stories is by Mike McKone, who has also illustrated many comics for DC and Marvel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Related Sites</strong><br />\r\n<a href="http://www.bigorrin.org/cree_kids.htm" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="Cree Kids">Cree Indian Fact Sheet</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.native-languages.org/cree-legends.htm" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="Cree legends">Cree Characters and Legends</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.fncaringsociety.com/about-shannen-koostachin" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="Shannen''s Dream">More information about Shannen Koostachin and her campaign</a></p>\r\n', 'Equinox-197x300.jpg', '1', '2015-02-13 09:51:54', 0),
(15, '氣候變化，而不是狩獵，殺害了乳齒象', 'Climate Change, Not Hunting, Killed Off Mastodons', '<p>在加拿大北部乳齒象很可能消滅了一個新的冰河時代的開始，而不是由人的獵人，根據一項新的科學研究。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>早期人類已普遍被指責為狩獵乳齒象滅絕在北美。但是，科學家們發現，曾經住在現在的阿拉斯加和育空地區已經滅絕了的第一個人類之前，乳齒象抵達該地區。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>乳齒象是遠親史前猛獁和現代大象。他們住在牛群的範圍遍布北美。乳齒象大約三米高，渾身毛茸茸的羊毛，而他們吃嫩枝，樹枝和其他森林植被。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>科學家們在研究了在北極發現36乳齒象化石。化石以前認為是約18000歲。但科學家懷疑已被用來保存化石材料已經干擾了約會的過程。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>他們刪除了所有的污染物質，然後用放射性碳測年來確定化石多大分別。試驗表明，他們至少50,000歲 - 這可以通過放射性碳測年來衡量的最早日期。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>科學家們現在認為，乳齒象生活在北極期間有短暫的&ldquo;間冰期&rdquo;時期。一個間冰期是二冷或&ldquo;冰川&rdquo;期間的氣溫回暖的時間。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>在末次間冰期從125000到75000年前的持續。在此期間，涵蓋暫時多少北美洲北部融化冰蓋和森林是能夠成長進一步北部。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>科學家們相信，乳齒象也搬再往北在此期間，繼樹和灌木，他們餵養。當溫度更冷再次轉向，植物死亡和乳齒象的食品供應消失。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>乳齒象北部的牛群可能會從寒冷和飢餓約75,000年前去世了。科學家們認為人類遷移到北美洲北部大約13000年前，所以都不見了北部乳齒象人類到來之前。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>南方牛群住了另一個65000年。他們的人數逐漸由於寒冷的氣溫和狩獵的組合有所下降。最後一個乳齒象北美大約10500年前消失了。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>一個誰曾在研究中，科學家是理查德&middot;哈靈頓，研究員自然加拿大博物館。他說，古生物學家一直想知道為什麼乳齒象是生活在北方的人的時候到了。當時，只有冰和草原，但沒有森林植被的乳齒象養活。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>現在，該化石的正確年齡已確定，這一切是有道理的，他說。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>相關網站</p>\r\n\r\n<p>美國乳齒象</p>\r\n', '<p>Mastodons in Canada&rsquo;s north were probably wiped out by the start of a new Ice Age, and not by human hunters, according to a new scientific study.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Early humans have commonly been blamed for hunting mastodons to extinction in North America. But scientists have discovered that the mastodons that once lived in what is now Alaska and the Yukon had already died out before the first humans arrived in the region.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mastodons were distantly related to prehistoric mammoths and modern-day elephants. They lived in herds that ranged all over North America. Mastodons were about three metres tall, covered in shaggy wool, and they ate twigs, branches and other forest vegetation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The scientists examined 36 mastodon fossils that had been found in the Arctic. The fossils were previously believed to be about 18,000 years old. But the scientists suspected that materials that had been used to preserve the fossils had interfered with the dating process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They removed all contaminating substances, then used&nbsp;<em>radiocarbon dating</em>&nbsp;to determine how old the fossils were. The tests showed they were at least&nbsp;50,000 years old &ndash; the oldest date that can be measured by radiocarbon dating.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The scientists now think that mastodons lived in the Artic during a brief &ldquo;interglacial&rdquo; period. An interglacial period is a time of warmer temperatures between two cold or &ldquo;glacial&rdquo; periods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The last interglacial period lasted from 125,000 to 75,000 years ago. During that time, ice sheets that covered much of northern North America melted temporarily and forests were able to grow further north.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The scientists believe mastodons also moved further north during this time, following the trees and shrubs they fed on. When the temperatures turned colder again, the plants died and the mastodon&rsquo;s food supply vanished.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The northern herds of mastodons likely died out from cold and starvation about 75,000 years ago. Scientists believe humans migrated into northern North America about 13,000 years ago, so the northern mastodons were gone before humans arrived.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Southern herds lived for another 65,000 years. Their numbers declined gradually due to a combination of colder temperatures and hunting. The last mastodons disappeared from North America about 10,500 years ago.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the scientists who worked on the study is Richard Harrington, a researcher at the Canadian Museum of Nature. He said paleontologists have always wondered why mastodons were living in the north when humans arrived. At that time, there was only ice and grassland, but no forest vegetation for mastodons to feed on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now that the correct age of the fossils has been determined, it all makes sense, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Related sites</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.beringia.com/research/mastadon.html" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="American mastodons">American mastodons</a></p>\r\n', '800px-Mastadon_SHS_museum_skeleton_by_Kevin_Saff-300x225.jpg', '3', '2015-02-13 09:53:52', 0),
(12, '一句傳世“皮埃爾乾酪澆肉汁土豆條”案', 'Sentence Handed Down In “Pierre Poutine” case', '<p>法官作出了對&ldquo;皮埃爾乾酪澆肉汁土豆條&rdquo;案的決定。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>皮埃爾乾酪澆肉汁土豆條的情況下<br />\r\n早在2011年，加拿大聯邦大選期間，一些人生活在安大略省圭爾夫接受敦促他們投票在手機上的信息。然而，該消息給了他們錯誤的方向投票站（你投的位置）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這些消息可能導致人去了錯誤的投票站投票。的時候，他們找到了合適的人，在那裡他們可以投票，投票可能會關閉或他們可能已經放棄了，決定回家來代替，而懶得去投票。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這本來是一個黨的知道，大多數人在某方面均打算投反對票，是一件好事。如果他們能阻止人們投票可言，他們將在選舉中成功。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這就是為什麼這樣的電話故意誤導選舉期間人是非法的。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6000多人收到誤導的信息。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>有一個調查的消息和電話被追踪到手機上屬於&ldquo;皮埃爾乾酪澆肉汁土豆條。&rdquo;這是用來隱藏真正的手機擁有者用假名。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>事實證明，負責消息的人之一是邁克爾索娜，誰曾為保守黨政黨。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>已進行了幾個月的試用後，索納已被判有罪的選舉欺詐行為。法官判處他九個月監禁。法官說，這是娑娜的初犯;他還指出，索納很可能不是一個人的工作，但沒有其他人已在帶電的情況下。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>一個CTV新聞故事列出了&ldquo;皮埃爾乾酪澆肉汁土豆條&rdquo;緋聞這裡事件的時間表。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>在該時間表，他們指出，在2012年2月，雙方索納和總理斯蒂芬&middot;哈珀否認有任何與該電話。哈珀指責試圖使保守黨看起來很糟糕的NDP和自由黨，CTV的新聞報告說。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>圭爾夫呼叫點一直以幫助保守黨馬蒂&middot;伯克民選，但是，該方案沒有工作，在這方面的一個自由黨候選人贏得。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>相關鏈接<br />\r\n有關這個案件的更多背景信息，閱讀這些文章TKN：</p>\r\n\r\n<p>http://teachingkidsnews.com/2012/02/29/two-canadian-political-parties-in-hot-water-over-use-of-technology/</p>\r\n\r\n<p>http://teachingkidsnews.com/2012/03/05/protests-and-accusations-the-robo-call-scandal-continues/</p>\r\n\r\n<p>課程連接<br />\r\n由喬納森&middot;蒂莉</p>\r\n', '<p>The judge has made a decision about the &ldquo;Pierre Poutine&rdquo; case.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The Pierre Poutine case</strong><br />\r\nBack in 2011, during a Canadian federal election, some people living in Guelph, Ontario received messages on their phones urging them to vote. However, the message gave them the wrong directions to the polling station (the location where you vote).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those messages may have caused people to go to the wrong polling station. By the time they found the right one, where they could vote, the polls may have closed or they may have given up and decided to go home instead and not bother to vote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That would have been a good thing for a party that knew that most of the people in a certain area were intending to vote against it. If they could prevent people from voting at all, they would be a successful in the election.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s why calls like that deliberately mislead people during an election are illegal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than 6,000 people received&nbsp;misleading messages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was an investigation into the messages and the calls were traced to a cell phone belonging to &ldquo;Pierre Poutine.&rdquo; That was a false name used to hide the real cell phone owner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It turns out, one of the people responsible for the messages was Michael Sona, who worked for the Conservative political party.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After a trial that has gone on for months, Sona has been found guilty of elections fraud. A judge sentenced him to nine months in jail. The judge said it was Sona&rsquo;s first offence; he also noted that Sona was likely not working alone, although no one else has been charged in the case.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A CTV news story lists a timeline of the events in the &ldquo;Pierre Poutine&rdquo; scandal&nbsp;<a href="http://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/robocalls-scandal-timeline-of-events-1.1960260" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="CTV timeline of Pierre Poutine news story">here</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In that timeline, they point out that in February, 2012, both Sona and Prime Minister Stephen Harper denied having anything to do with the calls. Harper accused the NDP and Liberals of trying to make the Conservatives look bad, CTV&rsquo;s news report says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The point of the Guelph calls had been to help get Conservative Marty Burke elected&ndash;however, the scheme didn&rsquo;t work and a Liberal candidate won in that area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Related links</strong><br />\r\nFor more background information about this case, read these TKN articles:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>http://teachingkidsnews.com/2012/02/29/two-canadian-political-parties-in-hot-water-over-use-of-technology/</p>\r\n\r\n<p>http://teachingkidsnews.com/2012/03/05/protests-and-accusations-the-robo-call-scandal-continues/</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CURRICULUM CONNECTIONS</strong><br />\r\nBy Jonathan Tilly</p>\r\n', '220px-Election_fraud_protester_on_Parliament_Hill.jpg', '5', '2015-02-13 09:48:33', 0),
(13, '影星在多倫多年度盛典', 'Movie Stars In Toronto For Annual Festival', '<p>每一年，電影明星，導演和製片人湧向多倫多。本週標誌著多倫多國際電影節（TIFF）的39年。這是一個為期10天的慶祝活動的電影，與首演（當影片被證明觀眾是第一次）和迷人的派對。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>整個城市進入電影瘋狂的10天的電影節期間。人們排隊等候檢查出一個有趣的新電影或紀錄片，並與其他電影愛好者聊天。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>貝爾TIFF燈箱，國王街多倫多市中心，是電影節的主會場，雖然電影是根據不少在市中心核心劇院。有數百節日期間顯示電影，從上午9點直到深夜。通常情況下，一個電影後表示，這部電影的明星上台回答了聽眾的提問。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>許多誰來到城市的節日掛在城市的豪華約克維爾區，那裡的球迷蜂擁而至，看看他們是否能抓拍照片或得到一個簽名的名人。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>數以百計的人還等在外面市區影院，因為他們知道自己最喜歡的演員將抵達在觀眾對他或她的電影首映。今年，訪問的城市著名演員包括小羅伯特&middot;唐尼，比爾&middot;默里，珍妮弗&middot;安妮斯頓，喬恩&middot;斯圖爾特，簡&middot;方達，傑森&middot;貝特曼和瑞茜&middot;威瑟斯彭。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>節日期間，人們誰有興趣拍電影扎堆專家學習，在特殊的講習班和研討會。人們也滿足銷售和推銷自己的電影。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>今年，TIFF擁有四個孩子的電影。每年4月，TIFF也承載了很大的兒童電影節，calledSprockets TIFF兒童國際電影節（4月7日至19日，2015年）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TIFF去從9月4日至今年14。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>感謝帕特Zelikovitz她與本文的幫助。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>相關鏈接<br />\r\n該網站的多倫多國際電影節。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>該網站為TIFF兒童國際電影節。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>課程連接<br />\r\n由凱瑟琳&middot;蒂莉</p>\r\n', '<p>Every year, movie stars, directors and producers flock to Toronto. This week marks the 39<span style="font-size:11px">th</span>&nbsp;year of the Toronto International Film Festival (TIFF). It&rsquo;s a 10-day long celebration of movies, with premieres (when a movie is shown to an audience for the first time) and glamorous parties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The whole city goes movie-mad during the 10-day festival. People wait in line to check out an interesting new movie or documentary and chat with fellow movie-lovers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Bell TIFF Lightbox, on King Street in downtown Toronto, is the festival&rsquo;s main theatre although movies are shown in a number of theatres in the downtown core. There are hundreds of movies shown during the festival, from 9 a.m. until late at night. Often, after a movie is shown, the stars of the movie go onstage to answer questions from the audience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many of the celebrities who come to the city for the festival hang out in the city&rsquo;s posh Yorkville district, where fans flock to see if they can snap a photo or get an autograph.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hundreds of people also wait outside downtown theatres because they know their favourite actor will arrive to be in the audience for the premiere of his or her film. This year, famous actors visiting the city include Robert Downey Jr., Bill Murray, Jennifer Aniston, Jon Stewart, Jane Fonda, Jason Bateman and Reese Witherspoon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During the festival, people who are interested in making movies get together to learn from experts at special workshops and seminars. People also meet to sell and market their movies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year, TIFF features four children&rsquo;s movies. In April every year, TIFF also hosts a big children&rsquo;s film festival, called<span style="color:rgb(153, 51, 0)"><del>Sprockets</del></span>&nbsp;TIFF Kids International Film Festival (April 7-19, 2015).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TIFF goes from Sept. 4 to 14 this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Thanks to Pat Zelikovitz for her assistance&nbsp;with this article.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Related link</strong><br />\r\nThe website for the&nbsp;<a href="http://www.tiff.net/" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="TIFF website">Toronto International Film Festival</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The website for&nbsp;<a href="http://www.tiff.net/festivals/tiffkidsfestival" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="TIFF Kids International Film Festival">TIFF Kids International Film Festival</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CURRICULUM CONNECTIONS</strong><br />\r\nBy&nbsp;Kathleen&nbsp;Tilly</p>\r\n', 'Morgan-Freeman-Diane-Keaton-Toronto-Star-300x278.jpg', '1', '2015-02-13 09:50:21', 0),
(11, '學校分歧嬰幼教室', 'Schools Divided Over Cellphones In Classrooms', '<p>在新斯科舍省上個月兩個高中學生之間的鬥爭已經強調了一些擔憂的父母和教師對學校的手機。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>當戰鬥爆發了兩個女孩之間在學校，其他學生記錄其與手機並將其上傳到網上。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>有的家長認為，戰鬥是蓄意挑起因此它可以實現共享上網。學校是擔心，因為一旦事情已經在網上公佈就很難把它刪除。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>學生使用手機已經迅速增加。約85％的品位11％的學生在加拿大現在有自己的手機。超過一半（52％），七年級的學生和24％的年級百分之四名學生還攜帶手機。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>很多學校說學生必須把自己的手機關閉，在上課時間讓他們在自己的背包或儲物櫃。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>其中取締手機的主要原因是，他們可以分散他們的工作的學生。許多這些手機是&ldquo;智能手機&rdquo;，這意味著它們也可以被用來上網，發短信，訪問社交媒體網站，玩遊戲，拍照和聽音樂。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>在最近的大學生在美國的調查顯示，學生們承認，他們在課堂上發送多達10個文本，並用自己的筆記本電腦的東西比其他功課的一半以上，他們在課堂上的時間。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>學校還禁止手機，因為他們擔心學生將用它們來欺騙測試，或記錄老師或其他同學的視頻，在網上張貼。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>許多家長擔心在學校使用手機。有人擔心，手機可用於網絡欺凌或安排打架。另一些人認為他們的孩子已經花太多時間使用手機和電腦。他們寧願讓他們聽，與人交談時，他們都在學校。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>但其他家長希望能夠在白天到達他們的孩子和贊成學校讓學生有機會獲得自己的手機。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這就是為什麼紐約市是解除其禁止手機在學校。截至目前為止，學生高中在城市還沒有被允許把他們的手機去上學。相反，很多離開他們在附近的商店，每天的收費大約一美元，以保持手機在上課時間。 （參見：日托為手機？TKN，4月25日，2014年）</p>\r\n\r\n<p>但紐約市長比爾&middot;白思豪說，他相信家長能在白天到達他們的孩子是非常重要的。現在城市的學校董事會正在試圖找到，讓手機在學校，但要避免的問題，他們可能會導致的最佳方式。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>有些人認為手機可能實際上是在學校裡非常有用。他們認為，教師應鼓勵學生利用他們在課堂上做研究在互聯網上或觀看教育視頻在網上。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這可能是在學校那裡有沒有足夠的計算機特別有用為每一個學生有一個。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>一些教師正在使用的手機應用程序，或&ldquo;應用程序&rdquo;，即讓學生工作在使用手機團體項目。還有一些應用程序，允許教師利用自己的手機來收集和分享物質，發出提醒類，並使用遊戲及相關的課堂作業測驗。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>贊成允許在學校使用手機的人說，今天的孩子在成長過程中所包圍的電子設備。學校的目標不應該是禁止手機，而是教會學生如何使用它們負責任。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>相關網站</p>\r\n\r\n<p>15有用的應用程序為教師和教育工作者</p>\r\n\r\n<p>耍小聰明！使用移動應用程序來提高你的教學</p>\r\n\r\n<p>課程連接<br />\r\n由凱瑟琳&middot;蒂莉</p>\r\n\r\n<p>寫作/討論提示<br />\r\n你有手機嗎？難道你的朋友有手機？如何以及什麼時候使用你的手機呢？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>你曾經使用他們學校的工作？如果是這樣，他們怎麼幫你？如果沒有，你認為手機應該在課堂上被允許？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>閱讀提示：查看點<br />\r\n有許多不同的觀點本文中討論。這些是什麼？是否有缺少任何觀點？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>初級<br />\r\n找出來看文本中提出，提問以確定丟失或觀點可能的替代點，並提出了一些可能的替代觀點。 （OME，閱讀：1.9）</p>\r\n\r\n<p>中間<br />\r\n確定視圖文本，包括日益複雜或難以呈現的文本點;給予它們可能含有任何偏見的證據;並提出其他可能的觀點。 （OME，閱讀：1.9）</p>\r\n\r\n<p>語言功能：短信語言<br />\r\n其中一個主要的使用，人們對手機的短信。文本意思是短消息。為了寫短信，人們經常寫使用&ldquo;短信語言&rdquo;。不要寫成例如，&ldquo;再見&rdquo;，他們可能會文本&ldquo;銅l8tr&rdquo;。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>什麼是文字講&#39;你知道嗎？</p>\r\n', '<p>A fight between two high school students in Nova Scotia last month has underlined some of the concerns parents and teachers have about cellphones in schools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the fight broke out between two girls at the school, another student recorded it with a cellphone and uploaded it to the Internet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some parents think the fight was deliberately provoked so it could be shared online. The school is concerned because once something has been posted online it can be difficult to get it removed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cellphone use among students has been increasing rapidly. About 85 per cent of grade 11 students in Canada now have their own cellphones. More than half (52 per cent) of grade seven students and 24 per cent of grade four students also carry cellphones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many schools say students must turn their phones off and leave them in their backpacks or lockers during school hours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the main reasons for banning cellphones is that they can distract students from their work. Many of these phones are &ldquo;smartphones,&rdquo; which means they can also be used to surf the Internet, send text messages, access social media sites, play games, take pictures and listen to music.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a recent survey of university students in the United States, the students admitted they sent as many as 10 texts during class, and used their laptops for things other than schoolwork for more than half the time they were in class.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Schools also ban cellphones because they are concerned that students will use them to cheat on tests, or to record videos of teachers or other students and post them online.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many parents are concerned about cellphone use at school. Some are worried that phones could be used for cyberbullying or to arrange fights. Others feel that their children already spend too much time using cellphones and computers. They would rather have them listening and talking to people when they are at school.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But other parents want to be able to reach their children during the day and are in favour of schools allowing students to have access to their phones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That is one reason why New York City is lifting its ban on cellphones in schools. Up until now, students at high schools in the city have not been allowed to bring their cellphones to school. Instead, many leave them at nearby stores that charge about a dollar a day to keep the phones during school hours. (See:&nbsp;<a href="http://teachingkidsnews.com/2014/04/25/4-daycare-cellphones/" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;">Daycare for Cellphones?</a>, TKN, April 25, 2014.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the mayor of New York, Bill de Blasio, says he believes it is very important for parents to be able to reach their children during the day. Now the city&rsquo;s school board is trying to find the best way to allow phones in schools but avoid the problems they can cause.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some people think cellphones could be actually be useful in school. They believe teachers should encourage students to use them in class to do research on the Internet or view educational videos online.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This can be especially useful in schools where there aren&rsquo;t enough computers for every student to have one.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some teachers are using cellphone applications, or &ldquo;apps,&rdquo; that allow students to work on group projects using their phones. There are also apps that allow teachers to use their phones to collect and share material, send out reminders to the class, and use games and quizzes related to class work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People in favour of allowing cellphone use in schools say that children today are growing up surrounded by electronic devices. The goal of schools should not be to ban cellphones, but to teach students how to use them responsibly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Related sites</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>15 Helpful&nbsp;<a href="http://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/best-apps-for-teachers-education/" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="Apps for teachers and educators">Apps for Teachers</a>&nbsp;and Educators</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.nea.org/home/41992.htm" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="Get Smart - using mobile apps to improve your teaching">Get Smart!</a>&nbsp;Using mobile apps to improve your teaching</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CURRICULUM CONNECTIONS</strong><br />\r\nBy Kathleen&nbsp;Tilly</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Writing/Discussion Prompt</strong><br />\r\nDo you have a cell phone? Do your friends have cell phones? How and when do you use your phones?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do you ever use them for school work? If so, how do they help you? If not, do you think phones should be allowed in classrooms?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reading Prompt:&nbsp;Point of View</strong><br />\r\nThere are many different points of view discussed in this article. What are they? Are there any perspectives that are missing?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Junior</em><br />\r\nIdentify the point of view presented in texts, ask questions to identify missing or possible alternative points of view, and suggest some possible alternative perspectives. (OME, Reading: 1.9)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Intermediate</em><br />\r\nIdentify the point of view presented in texts, including increasingly complex or difficult texts; give evidence of any biases they may contain; and suggest other possible perspectives.&nbsp;(OME, Reading: 1.9)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Language Feature: Texting Language&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nOne of the main uses that people have for cell phones is texting. Texts are meant to be short messages. In order to write short messages, people often write using &lsquo;texting language&rsquo;. For example, instead of writing &ldquo;see you later&rdquo;, they may text &ldquo;c u l8tr&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What &lsquo;text speak&rsquo; do you know?</p>\r\n', '320px-IPhone_at_Macworld_angled_view-171x300.jpg', '1', '2015-02-13 09:42:55', 0),
(10, '改變的時候了作為美國航空航天局升級其啟動時鐘', 'Time For A Change As NASA Upgrades Its Launch Clock', '<p>有一些非常有名的鐘錶世界：倫敦的大本鐘，並在和平塔在渥太華的時鐘，以名字只有兩個。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>但在世界上最受矚目的時鐘可能是美國宇航局的推出時鐘。倒計時發射航天器之前的秒數。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>但它的時間和它已被替換為新的，數字時鐘顯示圖像以及倒計時的發射時間。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>老鐘建於1969年，是高大約六英尺和26英尺寬。它向後計數，直到發射時間，直到推出的確切第二個，然後它的工作是算著，測量任務的時間。它的數字被點燃了一系列的40瓦的燈泡一樣，在人們的家中使用的那些。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>然而，隨著時間的推移著名的老鐘已經損壞的風，雨，陽光有時挑戰佛羅里達的氣候。它也一直難以NASA保持其舊技術，並保持在良好的工作秩序。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>新的時鐘是一個巨大的數字屏幕上，就像你可能在體育館看到的。它可以顯示任務的視頻，以及推出時間。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>新時鐘耗資NASA280000美元（美國）和約為7英尺高，26英尺的一面。它的第一份工作是今天推出的獵戶座飛船。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>老鐘已被轉移到NASA的遊客中心。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>寫作/討論提示<br />\r\n&ldquo;時間一變&rdquo;是一個雙關語。雙關語是使用不同含義的詞作說搞笑笑話。你能解釋一下在標題中一語雙關意味著什麼嗎？你有多少雙關語能想出這個故事？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>閱讀提示：了解擴展<br />\r\n今天的文章開始與下面的句子：&ldquo;有一些非常有名的鐘錶世界：倫敦的大本鐘，並在渥太華的和平塔，時鐘，命名只有兩個。&rdquo;為什麼是這兩個時鐘出名？你能想到的任何其他鐘錶是出名？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>初級<br />\r\n延長文本的理解通過連接想法他們自己的知識，經驗和見解，與其他熟悉的文本，以及他們周圍的世界（OME，閱讀：1.6）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>中間<br />\r\n延長文本的理解，包括日益複雜或難以文本，通過連接想法他們自己的知識，經驗和見解，與其他熟悉的文本，以及他們周圍的世界（OME，閱讀：1.6）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>語言功能：寫入號碼<br />\r\n有很多包含在這個故事中的數字。例如，下面的句子指出：&ldquo;老鐘建於1969年，是高大約六英尺和26英尺寬。&rdquo;在這句話中，數字使用的數字和字寫。為什麼他們寫的有什麼不同？什麼是怎麼寫數字的規則？</p>\r\n', '<p>There are some pretty famous clocks in the world: London&rsquo;s Big Ben, and the clock on the Peace Tower in Ottawa, to name just two.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the most watched&nbsp;clock in the world may be NASA&rsquo;s launch clock. It counts down the seconds before the launch of a spacecraft.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But its time was&nbsp;up and it has been replaced by a new,&nbsp;digital clock that shows images as well as counts down the launch time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The old clock was built in 1969 and was about six feet high and 26 feet wide. It counted backwards until&nbsp;the launch time until the exact second of the launch, and then its job was to count forward, to measure the time of the mission. Its numbers were lit up by a series of 40-watt lightbulbs, like the ones used in people&rsquo;s homes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, over time the famous old clock has been&nbsp;damaged by the wind, rain and sun in the sometimes challenging Florida climate. It has also been difficult for NASA to maintain its old technology and keep it in perfect working order.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new clock is an enormous digital screen, much like you might see in a sports stadium. It can show videos of the mission as well as the launch time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new clock cost NASA $280,000 (US) and is about seven feet high and 26 feet side. Its first job was today&rsquo;s launch of the Orion spacecraft.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The old clock has been&nbsp;moved to NASA&rsquo;s Visitor Centre.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Writing/Discussion Prompt</strong><br />\r\n&ldquo;Time for a change&rdquo; is a pun. A&nbsp;pun is a&nbsp;joke that uses different meanings of a word to make a&nbsp;saying funny. Can you explain what the pun in the title means? How many puns can you come up with for this story?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reading Prompt: Extending Understanding</strong><br />\r\nToday&rsquo;s article begins with the following sentence: &ldquo;There are some pretty famous clocks in the world: London&rsquo;s Big Ben, and the clock on the Peace Tower in Ottawa, to name just two.&rdquo; Why are these two clocks famous? Can you think of any other clocks that are famous?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Junior</em><br />\r\nExtend understanding of texts by connecting the ideas in them to their own knowledge, experience, and insights, to other familiar texts, and to the world around them (OME, Reading: 1.6).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Intermediate</em><br />\r\nExtend understanding of texts, including increasingly complex or difficult texts, by connecting the ideas in them to their own knowledge, experience, and insights, to other familiar texts, and to the world around them (OME, Reading: 1.6).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Language Feature: Writing Numbers</strong><br />\r\nThere are a lot of numbers included in this story. For&nbsp;example, the following sentence states: &ldquo;The old clock was built in 1969 and was about six feet high and 26 feet wide.&rdquo; In this sentence, numbers are written using numerals and words. Why are they written differently? What is the rule for how to write numbers?</p>\r\n', 'countdownclockmain_0-300x200.jpg', '5', '2015-02-13 09:41:22', 0);
INSERT INTO `tb_editor` (`editor_id`, `title_ch`, `title_en`, `description_ch`, `description_en`, `image`, `user_id`, `createdate`, `view_numbers`) VALUES
(8, 'Lammily娃娃都有現實的身材比例', 'Lammily Doll Has Realistic Body Proportions', '<p>Lammily是一種新的時尚娃娃，看起來更像是&ldquo;真實&rdquo;的女性，據它的設計者。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>藝術家尼古拉&middot;拉姆並沒有像一些&ldquo;時尚娃娃&rdquo;（例如，芭比娃娃）在建造時，非常薄，身材高大，不切實際的身體比例的方式。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>於是，他花了腰部，腿部，手臂和平均19歲婦女的其他測量和轉移下來到娃娃的大小。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>他想出了一個娃娃，使用測量，看上去更像是一個普通的女人。他的玩偶，他命名Lammily，是比較現實的期待。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;我想表明，平均是美麗的，&rdquo;他說，在一個宣傳視頻在其網站上。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>為了得到錢，創造的娃娃，他開始了整治互聯網去年三月。超過13600人給了他錢，以幫助他開始生產的娃娃。他們預購超過19000娃娃。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Lammily提倡健康的生活方式。她是適配性強，&ldquo;他說在他的網站。她穿著很少化妝，她的衣服是時尚，但運動感。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lammily，穿著白色運動鞋，牛仔短褲和上衣，銷售美國對拉姆的網站為25美元。她是11&ldquo;高，具有&rdquo;典型的&ldquo;人體比例。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這篇文章最初發表於TKN在2014年11月27日。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>課程連接<br />\r\n由喬納森&middot;蒂莉</p>\r\n\r\n<p>寫作/討論提示<br />\r\n該Lammily娃娃是所有其他娃娃不同，因為它使用了逼真的比例和尺寸。現在，之前為什麼沒有人發明了這樣的娃娃？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>你認為它會成功嗎？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>閱讀提示：了解擴展<br />\r\n玩具通常是由幻想製成，無論是機器人，士兵，或玩偶。如何你的玩具很多都設在幻想，有多少是真實的？為什麼你享受你自己的玩具種類玩？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>主<br />\r\n延長文本的理解通過連接想法他們自己的知識和經驗，為其他熟悉的文本，以及他們周圍的世界（OME，閱讀：1.6）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>初級<br />\r\n延長文本的理解通過連接想法他們自己的知識，經驗和見解，與其他熟悉的文本，以及他們周圍的世界（OME，閱讀：1.6）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>中間<br />\r\n延長文本的理解，包括日益複雜或難以文本，通過連接想法他們自己的知識，經驗和見解，與其他熟悉的文本，以及他們周圍的世界（OME，閱讀：1.6）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>語言特點：前綴（非）<br />\r\n前綴]是前置於另一個以改變它的含義的詞。今天的故事，包括單詞，&ldquo;不現實&rdquo;，這是受加入前綴&ldquo;UN&rdquo;做了一個字（意為不）和單詞&ldquo;現實&rdquo;。因此，單詞&ldquo;不現實&rdquo;的意思是&ldquo;沒有類似的東西是真實的。 &ldquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>使10個字使用前綴列表，不要怕有一些有趣的這個&ldquo;非&rdquo;;嘗試創建自己的一些新詞，其中包括他們的名單上了。</p>\r\n', '<p>Lammily is a new fashion doll that looks more like &ldquo;real&rdquo; women, according to its designer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Artist Nikolay Lamm didn&rsquo;t like the way some &ldquo;fashion dolls&rdquo; (for instance, Barbie dolls) are built to be very thin and tall, with unrealistic body proportions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So he took the waist, leg, arm and other measurements of average 19-year-old women and transferred them down to the size of a doll.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The doll he came up with, using the measurements, looked more like an average woman. His doll, which he named Lammily, is more realistic looking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I wanted to show that average is beautiful,&rdquo; he says in a promotional video on his website.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To get money to create the dolls, he started an Internet campaign last March. More than 13,600 people gave him money to help get him started producing the dolls. They pre-ordered more than 19,000 dolls.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Lammily promotes a healthy lifestyle. She is fit and strong,&rdquo; he says on his website. She wears very little make-up and her clothes are stylish but sporty.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lammily, wearing white running shoes, denim shorts and a blouse, sells for $25 U.S. on Lamm&rsquo;s website. She is 11&rdquo; high and has &ldquo;typical&rdquo; human body proportions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>This article was originally published on TKN on Nov. 27, 2014.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CURRICULUM CONNECTIONS</strong><br />\r\nBy Jonathan Tilly</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Writing/Discussion Prompt</strong><br />\r\nThe Lammily doll is different from all other dolls because it uses realistic proportions and sizes. Why hasn&rsquo;t someone invented a doll like this before now?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do you think it will be successful?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reading Prompt: Extending Understanding</strong><br />\r\nToys are often made from fantasy, whether it&rsquo;s robots, soldiers, or dolls. How many of your toys are based in fantasy and how many are realistic? Why do you enjoy playing with the types of toys that you own?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Primary</em><br />\r\nExtend understanding of texts by connecting the ideas in them to their own knowledge and experience, to other familiar texts, and to the world around them (OME, Reading: 1.6).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Junior</em><br />\r\nExtend understanding of texts by connecting the ideas in them to their own knowledge, experience, and insights, to other familiar texts, and to the world around them (OME, Reading: 1.6).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Intermediate</em><br />\r\nExtend understanding of texts, including increasingly complex or difficult texts, by connecting the ideas in them to their own knowledge, experience, and insights, to other familiar texts, and to the world around them (OME, Reading: 1.6).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Language Feature: Prefixes (un-)</strong><br />\r\nA prefix is a word that is placed before another in order to change its meaning. Today&rsquo;s story includes the word, &ldquo;unrealistic&rdquo; which is a word that is made by joining the prefix &ldquo;un&rdquo; (meaning not) and the word &ldquo;realistic.&rdquo; Accordingly, the word &ldquo;unrealistic&rdquo; means &ldquo;not resembling something that is real.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Make a list of 10 words that use the prefix &ldquo;un.&rdquo; Don&rsquo;t be afraid to have some fun with this; try to create some new words of your own and include them on your list too.</p>\r\n', 'Barbie-and-average-doll-Lammily-225x300.jpg,Lammily-doll-300x300.jpg', '4', '2015-02-13 09:39:07', 0),
(9, '另一個登錄消防', 'Another Log On The Fire', '<p>周圍有許多節日的傳統。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;節日傳統，&rdquo;在這種情況下，事情是人的節日，如聖誕節或光明節期間，每年都做。通常它是人們已經在很久以前做了很多年，也許開始。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>在聖誕節，例如，很多人豎起了聖誕樹和聖誕燈飾。這是聖誕節的傳統已經持續了很多年。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>但有一個&ldquo;新&rdquo;的聖誕傳統，已經變得非常流行：電視firelog。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這顯示不過是一個大壁爐，熊熊的壁爐的電視頻道。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>就是這樣。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>人們把它在電視上，這讓他們感覺自己在看，聽一個劈啪作響的火焰。這使他們感到平靜和舒適。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這一傳統始於加拿大在1986年當時，不是很多人知道這件事或看過的通道。今天，有超過300萬的人看在冬季節日火日誌通道。這一年，火日誌通道的建立是為了給誰的，現在被稱為邵氏電纜，在聖誕節休息公司工作過的員工。受假日期間運行的火日誌，每個人都可以回家了幾天，享受一點休息時間。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>當時，它只是廣播人在埃德蒙頓但今天它到達加拿大各地及以後的人。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>今年，肖火日誌進行了更新。他們打出了新的視頻在北溫哥華，不列顛哥倫比亞省一間小木屋裡。誰建的2014年大火的人是同一個誰建的火原在1986年。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>所述firelog實際上只燃燒30分鐘，然後將其上重複連續循環。展會的大興奮大約一半的方式，通過當一個人的手進入了一槍火捅了一下，使其變亮。人們樂趣想著那個男人，他是誰？人甚至寫信給肖電纜問他是否已婚。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>究竟是誰屬於&ldquo;即斯托克斯火手&rdquo;保持作為一個秘密，但肖證實，他不戴結婚戒指，他不嫁。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>如今，肖火日誌是非常高科技。雖然它仍然真的只是已經拍過火日誌，它有自己的Twitter帳戶（@ShawFireLog），其自己的Facebook頁面，它甚至有一個計算機應用程序，所以你可以看到在智能手機或平板電腦的燃燒日誌。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>肖火日誌將燒直到肖電纜1月5日，通道222。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這篇文章最初發表於TKN在2014年12月12日。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>課程連接<br />\r\n由喬納森&middot;蒂莉</p>\r\n\r\n<p>寫作/討論提示<br />\r\n你願意看火日誌通道或通道烤肉店15分鐘？為什麼呢？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>閱讀提示：推論<br />\r\n很多人對這個男人誰轉的日誌理論。你認為誰是他？什麼是他的故事？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>主<br />\r\n讓使用規定，並從文本隱含的想法作為證據（OME，閱讀：1.5）有關文本的推論。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>初級<br />\r\n使用明確和隱含的想法在文本做出推論和建構意義（OME，閱讀：1.5）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>中間<br />\r\n開發和使用說明明確和隱含的想法，從文本，以支持他們的解釋日益複雜或難以文本的解釋（OME，閱讀：1.5）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>語言特點：縮略語<br />\r\n的縮寫是已經縮短從它的實際形式的單詞。例如，今天的文章，包括縮寫，&ldquo;科技&rdquo;，&ldquo;科技&rdquo;是一個簡短形式的&ldquo;技術&rdquo;。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>你知道還有什麼其他的縮寫？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>為什麼會一個作家用完整的單詞的縮寫，在他們的寫作呢？<br />\r\n考慮至少三個不同的原因。</p>\r\n', '<p>There are many traditions around the holidays.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Holiday traditions,&rdquo; in this case are things that people do every year during a holiday such as Christmas or Hanukkah. Usually it is something that people have done for many years, perhaps beginning a long time ago.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At Christmas, for instance, many people put up a Christmas tree or Christmas lights. These are Christmas traditions that have been going on for many years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But there is a &ldquo;new&rdquo; Christmas tradition that has become very popular: The TV firelog.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s a TV channel that shows nothing but a large log fire, blazing in a fireplace.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People put it on their TV and it makes them feel like they are watching and listening to a crackling fire. It makes them feel calm and cosy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tradition started in Canada in 1986. At that time, not very many people knew about it or watched the channel. Today, more than three million people watch the fire log channel during the winter holiday season. That year, the fire log channel was created to give the staff who worked at the company that is now called Shaw Cable, a break at Christmas. By running the fire log during the holidays, everyone could go home for a few days and enjoy a bit of time off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At that time, it was only broadcast to people in Edmonton but today it reaches people across Canada and beyond.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year, the Shaw fire log was updated. They shot a new video inside a cabin in North Vancouver, British Columbia. The person who built the 2014 fire is the same one who built the original fire back in 1986.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The firelog really only burns for 30 minutes and then it is repeated on a continuous loop. The big excitement of the show is about half-way through when a man&rsquo;s hand comes into the shot to poke at the fire a bit to make it brighter. People have fun thinking about that man&mdash;who is he? People have even written to Shaw Cable to ask if he is married.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Exactly who belongs to &ldquo;the hand that stokes the fire&rdquo; is kept as a secret, but Shaw confirms that he doesn&rsquo;t wear a wedding ring&mdash;he is not married.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Today, the Shaw fire log is pretty high tech. Although it&rsquo;s still really just a fire log that has been filmed, it has its own Twitter account&nbsp;(@ShawFireLog), its own Facebook page and it even has a computer app so you can see the burning log on a smartphone or a tablet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Shaw fire log will burn until Jan. 5 on Shaw Cable, channel 222.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>This article was originally published on TKN on Dec. 12, 2014.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CURRICULUM CONNECTIONS</strong><br />\r\nBy Jonathan Tilly</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Writing/Discussion Prompt</strong><br />\r\nWould you rather watch 15 minutes of the fire log channel or the&nbsp;<a href="http://teachingkidsnews.com/2011/03/18/the-chicken-channel/" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank">rotisserie</a>&nbsp;channel? Why?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reading Prompt: Making Inferences</strong><br />\r\nMany people have&nbsp;theories about the man who turns the log. Who do you think he is? What is his story?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Primary</em><br />\r\nMake inferences about texts using stated and implied ideas from the texts as evidence (OME, Reading: 1.5).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Junior</em><br />\r\nUse stated and implied ideas in texts to make inferences and construct meaning (OME, Reading: 1.5).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Intermediate</em><br />\r\nDevelop and explain interpretations of increasingly complex or difficult texts using stated and implied ideas from the texts to support their interpretations (OME, Reading: 1.5).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Language Feature: Abbreviations</strong><br />\r\nAn abbreviation is a word that has been shortened from its actual form. For example, today&rsquo;s article includes the abbreviation, &ldquo;tech.&rdquo; &ldquo;Tech&rdquo; is a short form of &ldquo;technology.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What other abbreviations do you know?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why might an author use an abbreviation in their writing instead of the full word?<br />\r\nConsider at least three different reasons.</p>\r\n', '800px-Fireplace-RM-300x199.jpg', '3', '2015-02-13 09:39:07', 0),
(7, '雪橇禁止在一些加拿大和美國的城鎮', 'Tobogganing Banned In Some Canadian and US Towns', '<p>也被稱為&ldquo;雪橇&rdquo;雪橇是一項運動中，人們坐在塑料或木製平底雪橇在白雪皚皚的山頂......然後推了，去滑下山坡。它可以是令人興奮的，有點嚇人的，很多的樂趣。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這也是很好的鍛煉，特別是因為你已經滑了下來後山上，你通常要往回走了。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>有人說雪橇可能是危險的，因為它是可能的雪橇給小費還是碰到了什麼東西的路上下來，就很難停下來。人尤其是兒童，也受到傷害。誰也得到傷害甚至可能再責怪這個城市對他們的事故和控告城市的一些人（起訴，在這種情況下，讓城市付給他們一些錢）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>這就是為什麼在加拿大和美國一些城市最近禁止雪橇。其他城鎮已經把限制上山上的人可以在雪橇。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>人誰無視禁令和雪橇上不得不支付罰款已被取締的風險的一座小山上。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>有些人反對在雪橇新的禁令。漢密爾頓人，安大略省組建一個網上請願書，要求，而不是禁止雪橇的是，這座城市豎起跡象表明說&ldquo;雪橇需要您自擔風險&rdquo;代替。這樣一來，他們說，人們可以自己決定，如果他們想冒這個險。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>雪橇是一種廉價，有趣，有時甚至是危險的冬季運動。醫生說，人誰雪橇應該戴頭盔，這可能有助於防止一些傷害。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>在一些城市，如渥太華，安大略省和阿爾伯塔省卡爾加里，但是也有一些專門扶植對這項運動的&ldquo;官方&rdquo;雪橇小山。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>像許多體育，雪橇可能是危險的，但它也可以是很好的鍛煉，並有很多樂趣。現在來看，它仍然發生在許多小山在北美白雪皚皚的城鎮。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>相關網站</p>\r\n\r\n<p>漢密爾頓的網上請願書。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>課程連接<br />\r\n由喬納森&middot;蒂莉</p>\r\n\r\n<p>寫作/討論提示<br />\r\n你認為應該toboganning一些山頭被禁止？你認為一個城市的作用，如果他們張貼的警告足夠負責任？你想怎麼看這個問題解決了嗎？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>閱讀提示：查看點<br />\r\n你認為哪一方的說法，今天的故事的作家嗎？你可以支持你的答案文本找到什麼證據？</p>\r\n\r\n<p>主<br />\r\n確定視圖中的文本呈現的點，並提出了一些可能的替代觀點（OME，閱讀：1.9）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>初級<br />\r\n找出來看文本中提出，提問以確定丟失或觀點可能的替代點，並提出了一些可能的替代觀點（OME，閱讀：1.9）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>中間<br />\r\n確定視圖文本，包括日益複雜或難以呈現的文本點;給予它們可能含有任何偏見的證據;並提出其他可能的觀點（OME，閱讀：1.9）。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>語言功能：文字起源<br />\r\n後來，這個詞被通過了英語，其形式單詞&ldquo;雪橇&rdquo;其實是一個Mi&#39;kmac意思是&ldquo;雪橇&rdquo;。法裔加拿大人開始使用這個詞隨著時間的推移，開始指雪橇為&ldquo;tabaganne。&rdquo;，&ldquo;雪橇&rdquo;。</p>\r\n\r\n<p>在只使用字母&ldquo;雪橇&rdquo;，使新詞的列表。新詞不必使用所有8個字母。您的列表比作朋友。誰得到了更多的話嗎？</p>\r\n', '<p>Also known as &ldquo;sledding,&rdquo; tobogganing is a sport in which people sit on a plastic or wooden flat-bottomed sled at the top of a snowy hill&hellip; and then push off, to go sliding down the hill. It can be exciting, a bit scary and lots of fun.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s also great exercise, especially since after you&rsquo;ve slid down the hill, you usually have to walk back up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some people say tobogganing can be dangerous, since it&rsquo;s possible for the sled to tip or hit something on the way down and it can be difficult to stop. People&mdash;especially children&mdash;can get hurt. Some people who have gotten hurt may even then blame the city for their accident and sue the city (<em>sue</em>, in this case, make the city pay them some money).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s why some towns in Canada and the United States have recently banned tobogganing. Other towns have put limits on which hills people can toboggan on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People who ignore the ban and toboggan on a hill that has been banned risk having to pay a fine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some people are objecting to the new bans on tobogganing. People in Hamilton, Ontario put together an online petition, asking that instead of banning tobogganing, the city put up signs that say &ldquo;Toboggan at your own risk&rdquo; instead. That way, they say, people can decide for themselves if they want to take the risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tobogganing is an inexpensive, fun and sometimes dangerous winter sport. Doctors say that people who toboggan should wear a helmet, which may help to prevent some injuries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In some cities, like Ottawa, Ontario and Calgary, Alberta, there are &ldquo;official&rdquo; tobogganing hills that are specifically groomed for the sport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like many sports, tobogganing can be dangerous, but it can also be great exercise and a lot of fun. And for now, it&rsquo;s still happening on many hills in snowy towns across North America.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Related site</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hamilton&rsquo;s&nbsp;<a href="https://www.change.org/p/city-of-hamilton-let-us-toboggan" style="color: rgb(0, 66, 118); text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="Hamilton online petition against tobogganing ban">online petition</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CURRICULUM CONNECTIONS</strong><br />\r\nBy Jonathan Tilly</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Writing/Discussion Prompt</strong><br />\r\nDo you think toboganning should be banned from some hills? Do you think a city is acting sufficiently responsible if they post warnings? How would you like to see this problem solved?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Reading Prompt: Point of View</strong><br />\r\nWhat side of the argument do you think the writer of today&rsquo;s story is on? What evidence can you find in the text to support your answer?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Primary</em><br />\r\nIdentify the point of view presented in a text and suggest some possible alternative perspectives&nbsp;(OME, Reading: 1.9).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Junior</em><br />\r\nIdentify the point of view presented in texts, ask questions to identify missing or possible alternative points of view, and suggest some possible alternative perspectives&nbsp;(OME, Reading: 1.9).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>Intermediate</em><br />\r\nIdentify the point of view presented in texts, including increasingly complex or difficult texts; give evidence of any biases they may contain; and suggest other possible perspectives&nbsp;(OME, Reading: 1.9).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Language Feature:&nbsp;Word Origin</strong><br />\r\nThe word &ldquo;toboggan&rdquo; is actually a Mi&rsquo;kmac word meaning &ldquo;sled.&rdquo; French-Canadians started to use the word over time and began to refer to sledding as &ldquo;tabaganne.&rdquo; Later, the word was adopted by English, and its form, &ldquo;toboggan.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using only the letters in &ldquo;toboggan,&rdquo; make a list of new words. New words don&rsquo;t have to use all 8 letters. Compare your list to a friend&rsquo;s. Whose got more words?</p>\r\n', 'Toboggan-Toronto-Star-2-192x300.jpg', '2', '2015-02-13 09:36:28', 0);

